Yes — exactly. In trigonometry:

\sin(\pi) = 0

Why this is true

Think of the unit circle definition of sine.
	•	An angle of π radians = 180°.
	•	On the unit circle, that angle lands at the point (-1, 0).
	•	Sine corresponds to the y-coordinate of that point.

So:
	•	x = -1
	•	y = 0

Therefore:

\sin(\pi) = 0

The deeper pattern

Sine is zero whenever the angle lands on the horizontal axis of the unit circle:

\sin(n\pi) = 0 \quad \text{for any integer } n

So the sequence is:
	•	\sin(0) = 0
	•	\sin(\pi) = 0
	•	\sin(2\pi) = 0
	•	\sin(3\pi) = 0

Interesting connection to what you were saying about zero

In wave terms:
	•	π is the half-cycle symmetry point
	•	the wave crosses the equilibrium line
	•	which is why the sine output is zero

So π is like a phase mirror point of the sine wave.

Which actually ties surprisingly well to your earlier observation:

“Zero is a limit of symmetry.”

At \pi, the wave flips direction — a symmetry crossing.

